00:48:56,309 --> 00:48:59,437
You really seemed to like the book,
The Count of Monte Cristo.

719
00:48:59,520 --> 00:49:03,274
It's my favorite.
I liked it more since I've been in here.

720
00:49:03,358 --> 00:49:04,859
Why is that?

721
00:49:05,818 --> 00:49:09,405
It's like, he wouldn't let anyone beat him,
the Count.

722
00:49:10,239 --> 00:49:14,077
Took what he had to take,
beatings, insults, and whatever.

723
00:49:15,078 --> 00:49:16,913
And he learned from it.

724
00:49:16,996 --> 00:49:21,292
Then when the time came for him
to do something, he made his move.

725
00:49:22,001 --> 00:49:24,879
-You admire that?
-No, I respect that.

726
00:49:27,048 --> 00:49:29,384
You got a copy of the book at home?

727
00:49:29,467 --> 00:49:32,261
I got the Classics Illustrated Comic.

728
00:49:32,345 --> 00:49:33,972
It's not the same thing.

729
00:49:34,055 --> 00:49:36,599
Listen, I gotta go.
I'm gonna miss morning roll call.

730
00:49:36,683 --> 00:49:39,769
Wait one minute. I've got something for you.

731
00:49:41,396 --> 00:49:44,732
-I thought you might like to have it.
-SHAKES: Are you serious?

732
00:49:44,816 --> 00:49:48,319
You love the book that much.
You should have a copy of your own.

733
00:49:48,403 --> 00:49:50,822
-I can't pay you.
-It's a gift.

734
00:49:51,656 --> 00:49:55,326
-You've gotten gifts before, haven't you?
-It's been a while.

735
00:49:55,410 --> 00:49:58,663
-it's my way of saying thanks.
-For what?

736
00:50:00,039 --> 00:50:03,376
That somebody listens,
even if it's just one student.

737
00:50:03,459 --> 00:50:05,169
You're a good teacher, Mr. Carlson.

738
00:50:05,253 --> 00:50:07,338
We can discuss the book on Friday in class

739
00:50:07,422 --> 00:50:09,674
if you think the Count
can hold their attention.

740
00:50:09,757 --> 00:50:11,175
He's got a shot.

741
00:50:11,259 --> 00:50:13,469
Any particular section I should read from?

742
00:50:13,553 --> 00:50:16,973
That's easy.
The part where he escapes from prison.

743
00:50:29,736 --> 00:50:32,697
There you go, star. Here's your locker room.

744
00:50:40,121 --> 00:50:44,751
SHAKES: It was only a game,
just a touch football game, nothing more.

745
00:50:45,585 --> 00:50:48,004
But a game I wish we had never played.

746
00:50:48,087 --> 00:50:52,050
Guards against inmates.
The guards practiced four times a week.

747
00:50:52,925 --> 00:50:55,803
Our team was picked
the Monday before the game.

748
00:50:55,887 --> 00:50:59,474
We had a two-hour practice.
It didn't matter much.

749
00:50:59,557 --> 00:51:03,519
We weren't supposed to win.
We were just supposed to show up.

750
00:51:03,603 --> 00:51:07,398
-Who's the toughest guy out here?
-How do you mean, tough?

751
00:51:07,648 --> 00:51:12,070
-Who can talk and have everyone listen?
-Rizzo. Black kid over there.

752
00:51:13,529 --> 00:51:17,116
SHAKES: Michael saw an opening,
a chance to bring the game to our level,

753
00:51:17,200 --> 00:51:21,329
even out the Held.
But he needed help. He needed Rizzo.

754
00:51:21,954 --> 00:51:26,209
Black kid with an Italian name.
With Rizzo on our side, we had a chance.

755
00:51:27,085 --> 00:51:29,962
Look, white boy,
I don't know what you play in the streets.

756
00:51:30,046 --> 00:51:32,632
I don't care.
But in here, the guards call the play

757
00:51:32,715 --> 00:51:35,718
-and the play calls for them to win the game.
-Why?

758
00:51:36,636 --> 00:51:40,223
Guards steer clear of me, all right?
They stay back and let me do my time.

759
00:51:40,306 --> 00:51:44,060
If I play that game and hurt one of them,
they just might change my cushion.

760
00:51:44,143 --> 00:51:47,855
MICHAEL: I'm not saying we gotta win.
I just don't want to take a beating.

761
00:51:47,939 --> 00:51:49,482
RIZZO: You do, every day.

762
00:51:49,565 --> 00:51:53,486
-Why is Saturday special?
-'Cause on Saturday, we can hit back.

763
00:51:55,530 --> 00:51:59,534
They don't fuck with you like they do us,
but they fuck with you in another way.

764
00:51:59,617 --> 00:52:01,536
You're just an animal to them.

765
00:52:01,619 --> 00:52:04,205
-I don't give a fuck.
-Yeah, you do.

766
00:52:04,455 --> 00:52:07,917
And beating them on Saturday
is not gonna change a thing.

767
00:52:08,000 --> 00:52:09,418
Then why, white boy?

768
00:52:09,502 --> 00:52:13,923
To make them feel what we feel.
Just for a couple of hours.

769
00:52:15,967 --> 00:52:17,927
Now, don't try anything funny, Sambo.

770
00:52:18,010 --> 00:52:20,471
Nobody will get hurt.
You know what I'm saying?

771
00:52:20,555 --> 00:52:22,932
-I call heads.
-REFEREE: He calls heads.

772
00:52:24,559 --> 00:52:26,894
REFEREE: He called heads. It is a head.

773
00:52:28,729 --> 00:52:30,064
Let's go.

774
00:52:31,566 --> 00:52:33,651
(PLAYERS GRUNTING)

775
00:52:35,987 --> 00:52:37,405
(NOKES GRUNTING IN PAIN)

776
00:52:39,782 --> 00:52:43,578
You're gonna die, motherfucker.
You're gonna fucking die.

777
00:52:43,661 --> 00:52:45,621
(PLAYERS GRUNTING)

778
00:52:53,754 --> 00:52:55,756
None of you motherfuckers can cover me!

779
00:52:55,840 --> 00:52:59,343
We got ourselves a game!
I'm feeling good today.

780
00:52:59,760 --> 00:53:01,637
This shit feels good.

781
00:53:14,192 --> 00:53:15,234
GUARD 1: Fuck!

782
00:53:15,318 --> 00:53:16,861
GUARD 2: Get the fuck off of me!

783
00:53:29,373 --> 00:53:31,876
Yeah, keep smiling, you little pissant.

784
00:53:34,670 --> 00:53:37,757
SHAKES: For 90 minutes,
we took the game out of the prison,

785
00:53:37,840 --> 00:53:39,759
moved it miles beyond the locked gates

786
00:53:39,842 --> 00:53:42,678
and the sloping hills
of the surrounding countryside,

787
00:53:42,762 --> 00:53:46,682
and brought it back down to the streets
of the neighborhoods we'd come from.

788
00:53:46,766 --> 00:53:49,894
For those 90 minutes,
we were once again free.

789
00:53:49,977 --> 00:53:52,355
(PLAYERS YELLING)

790
00:53:55,775 --> 00:53:58,486
(INMATES CHEERING)

791
00:54:00,947 --> 00:54:02,365
(WHOOPING)

792
00:54:06,077 --> 00:54:09,247
INMATES: (CHANTING) Rizzo! Rizzo!

793
00:54:13,542 --> 00:54:15,169
(CHANTING CONTINUES)I

794
00:54:21,676 --> 00:54:23,094
(SOFTLY) Rizzo.

795
00:54:27,598 --> 00:54:30,768
Nokes, good game.

796
00:54:33,604 --> 00:54:36,941
SHAKES: For once, we had a victory.
But it didn't last.

797
00:54:37,525 --> 00:54:39,235
It couldn't last.

798
00:54:39,860 --> 00:54:42,321
And all I wanted to do was die.

799
00:54:42,989 --> 00:54:44,782
I was not alone in the hole.

800
00:54:44,865 --> 00:54:47,535
I knew my friends
were down in the depths with me.

801
00:54:47,618 --> 00:54:52,081
Each in his own cell, each in his own pain,
suffering his own demons.

802
00:54:52,290 --> 00:54:54,208
Rizzo was there, too.

803
00:54:56,627 --> 00:54:58,921
I had lost any sense of time.

804
00:55:17,815 --> 00:55:19,191
(LAUGHING)

805
00:55:38,919 --> 00:55:41,297
I thought you'd never wake up.

806
00:55:41,380 --> 00:55:43,257
SHAKES: I thought I'd never want to.

807
00:55:43,341 --> 00:55:46,552
John and Tommy,
they're on the other side there.

808
00:55:47,970 --> 00:55:49,472
How are they?

809
00:55:50,973 --> 00:55:52,475
They're alive.

810
00:55:53,434 --> 00:55:54,852
Who isn't?

811
00:55:56,479 --> 00:55:57,772
Rizzo.

812
00:56:00,149 --> 00:56:01,859
They killed him?

813
00:56:03,235 --> 00:56:07,656
They took turns beating him
until there was nothing of that kid to beat.

814
00:56:12,203 --> 00:56:14,497
SHAKES: Rizzo was dead because of us.

815
00:56:14,705 --> 00:56:17,291
We made him think
that going up against the guards

816
00:56:17,375 --> 00:56:20,544
in a meaningless football game
had some value,

817
00:56:20,628 --> 00:56:23,339
that it would give us a reason to go on.

818
00:56:23,422 --> 00:56:25,508
Once again, we were wrong.

819
00:56:28,511 --> 00:56:30,179
TOMMY: Did they give you a release date yet?

820
00:56:30,262 --> 00:56:31,931
SHAKES: Nokes had a letter from the warden.

821
00:56:32,014 --> 00:56:34,725
Waved it in front of me, then tore it up.

822
00:56:35,184 --> 00:56:37,019
MICHAEL: When do you figure?

823
00:56:37,144 --> 00:56:40,898
I don't know. End of spring,
early summer, or something.

824
00:56:41,107 --> 00:56:43,567
I wish we were coming with you.

825
00:56:43,651 --> 00:56:47,196
It would've been nice
for all of us to walk out together.

826
00:56:47,279 --> 00:56:51,784
No use thinking about that.
We're gonna do a full year, not an hour less.

827
00:56:52,827 --> 00:56:56,372
When I get out, I could get Father Bobby
to make a couple of phone calls.

828
00:56:56,455 --> 00:56:57,665
Shave a month or two off.

829
00:56:57,748 --> 00:57:01,043
-There's nothing to talk about.
-There's a lot to talk about.

830
00:57:01,127 --> 00:57:04,547
Maybe if people knew what was going on
in here, they'd make a move.

831
00:57:04,630 --> 00:57:06,966
I don't want anybody to know.

832
00:57:07,049 --> 00:57:10,719
Not Father Bobby, King Benny, Fat Mancho,

833
00:57:10,803 --> 00:57:13,097
not my mother. Nobody.

834
00:57:14,765 --> 00:57:16,100
TOMMY: Yeah, I don't, either.

835
00:57:16,183 --> 00:57:19,353
I mean, l wouldn't know
what to say to anyone who did know.

836
00:57:19,437 --> 00:57:22,857
MICHAEL: I can't think of anybody
who needs to hear about it.

837
00:57:23,190 --> 00:57:26,735
Either they won't believe it,
or they won't give a shit.

838
00:57:26,819 --> 00:57:30,448
Yeah, I don't even think we should
talk about it once it's over.

839
00:57:31,323 --> 00:57:35,870
We got no choice but to live with it.
And talking makes living it harder.

840
00:57:36,704 --> 00:57:39,540
So we might as well not even talk about it.

841
00:57:39,623 --> 00:57:41,750
The truth stays with us.

842
00:57:44,545 --> 00:57:47,381
I want to be able to sleep one night

843
00:57:47,882 --> 00:57:52,386
and not have to worry who's coming
in my room, what's gonna happen to me.

844
00:57:55,055 --> 00:57:59,101
If I can get that, then I'll be happy.

845
00:58:01,896 --> 00:58:04,440
Someday, John. I promise.

846
00:58:21,415 --> 00:58:25,127
SHAKES: I was in my last hours as an inmate
at the Wilkinson Home for Boys.

847
00:58:25,419 --> 00:58:30,257
1 was given four copies of my release form. The final reminder of my time at Wilkinson.

848
00:58:32,176 --> 00:58:34,720
I never heard the key turn in the lock

849
00:58:34,803 --> 00:58:37,765
and I never heard the snap of the bolt.

850
00:58:38,599 --> 00:58:40,518
NOKES: You should be asleep.

851
00:58:40,976 --> 00:58:44,939
I just wanted to say good-bye. We all do.

852
00:58:47,983 --> 00:58:49,610
NOKES: I told him right to his face.

853
00:58:49,693 --> 00:58:52,112
I said, "I don't care
if you're paying me overtime.

854
00:58:52,196 --> 00:58:53,864
"I'm not working those kind of hours."

855
00:58:53,948 --> 00:58:56,450
FERGUSON: Yeah, but you put in for it?
NOKES: Yeah, I did.

856
00:58:56,534 --> 00:58:59,078
FERGUSON: 'Cause I put in for it,
and they don't give it.

857
00:58:59,161 --> 00:59:02,706
I come in early for three days,
do they give me overtime? No.

858
00:59:03,290 --> 00:59:06,210
SHAKES: A part of all of us
was left there that night.

859
00:59:06,293 --> 00:59:09,255
A night that will
never be removed from my mind.

860
00:59:09,338 --> 00:59:14,009
That night of June 1, 1968,
the summer of love.

861
00:59:15,302 --> 00:59:18,389
My last night
at the Wilkinson Home for Boys.

862
00:59:37,658 --> 00:59:40,119
(CARS HONKING)

863
01:00:04,101 --> 01:00:07,271
SHAKES: At 8:25 p.m.,
two men walked through the doors.

864
01:00:07,354 --> 01:00:11,150
The bartender knew their faces as most
of the neighborhood knew their names.

865
01:00:11,233 --> 01:00:14,194
They were two of the founding members
of the West Side Boys.

866
01:00:14,278 --> 01:00:16,572
They were also its deadliest.

867
01:00:17,364 --> 01:00:21,076
The blond-haired man had been
in and out of jail since he was a teenager

868
01:00:21,201 --> 01:00:23,954
He robbed and killed at will, or on command.

869
01:00:24,038 --> 01:00:27,166
He's presently a suspect
in four unsolved homicides.

870
01:00:27,249 --> 01:00:31,337
He was an alcoholic and a cocaine abuser
with a fast temper and a faster trigger

871
01:00:31,420 --> 01:00:35,883
He once shot a mechanic dead
for moving ahead of him in a movie line.

872
01:00:36,383 --> 01:00:38,469
The dark-haired man was equally deadly

873
01:00:38,552 --> 01:00:41,597
and had committed his first murder
at the age of 17.

874
01:00:41,722 --> 01:00:43,891
In return, he was paid $50.

875
01:00:44,224 --> 01:00:45,726
He drank and he did drugs

876
01:00:45,809 --> 01:00:49,730
and he had a wife he never sew,
living somewhere in Queens.

877
01:00:55,903 --> 01:00:57,488
(MEN CHATTERING)

878
01:00:58,238 --> 01:01:02,326
-it'll take more than four years to get...
-They'll take it at the mid-term elections.

879
01:01:02,409 --> 01:01:05,204
BUSINESSMAN 1: He's got the charisma.
He's gonna do it.

880
01:01:05,287 --> 01:01:08,165
BUSINESSMAN 2: He's our man.
Reagan's the man who's gonna do it.

881
01:01:09,500 --> 01:01:12,294
Hey, Jerry. Who are they talking about?

882
01:01:12,419 --> 01:01:15,089
They're talking about Reagan's speech.

883
01:01:17,299 --> 01:01:20,636
Order those two men some drinks
and put it on my tab.

884
01:01:21,595 --> 01:01:24,765
Tell them that Republicans
are not welcome in Hell's Kitchen,

885
01:01:24,848 --> 01:01:28,852
and either a political conversion
or a change of conversation is in order.

886
01:01:28,936 --> 01:01:30,437
Sure thing.

887
01:01:33,941 --> 01:01:35,984
-Gentlemen.
-Yeah?

888
01:01:36,652 --> 01:01:39,988
The gentlemen there would like to
buy you a drink on one condition.

889
01:01:40,114 --> 01:01:43,784
You know the rules, no religion, no politics.

890
01:01:44,451 --> 01:01:46,286
You get my meaning?

891
01:01:54,253 --> 01:01:56,296
(MAN CHATTERING ON TV)

892
01:02:03,137 --> 01:02:06,515
Order something for me.
I gotta go to the bathroom.

893
01:02:27,661 --> 01:02:29,705
(METALLIC CLANKING)

894
01:02:36,503 --> 01:02:39,173
Can I help you with something, chief?

895
01:02:39,506 --> 01:02:41,091
