1417
01:39:47,440 --> 01:39:49,651
I like to eat a little light in the day.

1418
01:39:49,734 --> 01:39:52,946
A martini, two glasses of wine,
and a salad. Is that correct?

1419
01:39:53,029 --> 01:39:54,781
Yes, that's right.

1420
01:39:54,864 --> 01:39:59,619
And then you had wine at dinner,
about six hours later. Is that right?

1421
01:39:59,703 --> 01:40:01,037
MRS. SALINAS: Yes, that's right.

1422
01:40:01,121 --> 01:40:02,872
How much wine did you have to drink

1423
01:40:02,956 --> 01:40:05,458
by the time my clients allegedly
walked into McHale's?

1424
01:40:05,542 --> 01:40:09,379
-Two glasses.
-Would you say that four glasses of wine

1425
01:40:10,005 --> 01:40:14,092
and a martini within a six-hour period
is a lot for you to drink?

1426
01:40:14,175 --> 01:40:15,677
Yes, it is.

1427
01:40:21,599 --> 01:40:25,854
Have you ever heard a gun fired,
prior to the night in question?

1428
01:40:26,396 --> 01:40:27,564
No.

1429
01:40:29,232 --> 01:40:33,570
-How would you describe the sound?
-It was loud. Like fireworks loud.

1430
01:40:35,196 --> 01:40:39,159
-Did the sound frighten you?
-MRS. SALINAS: Very much.

1431
01:40:39,951 --> 01:40:42,037
Did you close your eyes?

1432
01:40:43,621 --> 01:40:46,708
At first, until the shooting stopped.
Then I opened them.

1433
01:40:46,791 --> 01:40:51,337
Did you think the men who did the shooting
were going to kill everybody in McHale's?

1434
01:40:51,421 --> 01:40:55,550
I really didn't know what to think.
I just knew that the man had been snot.

1435
01:40:55,633 --> 01:41:00,138
Did you think you might be shot dead
by the two cold-blooded killers?

1436
01:41:01,014 --> 01:41:02,390
Yes, I did.

1437
01:41:02,474 --> 01:41:06,770
Yet despite that fear,
despite that risk to your life,

1438
01:41:06,895 --> 01:41:10,857
you looked at their faces as they left?

1439
01:41:12,067 --> 01:41:14,402
-Yes, I did.
-Is that correct?

1440
01:41:15,445 --> 01:41:16,863
Yes, I did.

1441
01:41:17,072 --> 01:41:19,949
Did you look at their faces? Did you

1442
01:41:20,033 --> 01:41:23,161
really look, Mrs. Salinas?

1443
01:41:24,454 --> 01:41:27,415
I glanced at them when they walked by,
but I did see them.

1444
01:41:27,499 --> 01:41:29,626
You glanced?

1445
01:41:30,085 --> 01:41:31,836
You didn't look?

1446
01:41:32,295 --> 01:41:34,005
I saw them.

1447
01:41:34,756 --> 01:41:37,258
You glanced at them, Mrs. Salinas.

1448
01:41:37,342 --> 01:41:41,304
You glanced at them through the eyes
of a very frightened woman

1449
01:41:41,387 --> 01:41:44,182
who maybe had too much to drink.

1450
01:41:44,891 --> 01:41:47,602
-Objection, Your Honor.
-SNYDER: There is no need, Your Honor.

1451
01:41:47,685 --> 01:41:49,270
I have no further questions.

1452
01:41:49,354 --> 01:41:52,315
WEISMAN: Thank you, Mrs. Salinas.
You may step down.

1453
01:41:55,693 --> 01:41:57,779
SHAKES: It was 6:15 on Sunday morning.

1454
01:41:57,862 --> 01:42:01,032
Frank Magcicco worked
out of a homicide unit in Brooklyn.

1455
01:42:01,116 --> 01:42:05,120
He was a first-grade detective
with an honest name and a solid reputation.

1456
01:42:05,203 --> 01:42:07,497
He was also King Benny's nephew.

1457
01:42:07,580 --> 01:42:10,500
Nick Davenport was with Internal Affairs.

1458
01:42:10,583 --> 01:42:13,503
He was ambitious and wanted
to make captain before he hit 40.

1459
01:42:13,586 --> 01:42:15,463
He knew the fastest way up the track

1460
01:42:15,547 --> 01:42:19,551
was to reel in a maximum amount
of dirty cops in a minimum amount of time.

1461
01:42:19,634 --> 01:42:21,344
Frank, what is this shit?

1462
01:42:21,427 --> 01:42:23,346
If I were you, I'd do what the kid says.

1463
01:42:23,429 --> 01:42:27,267
You make this, you'll be having breakfast
once a month with the Commissioner.

1464
01:42:27,392 --> 01:42:30,895
You got a real hard-on for this Styler guy.
What's your beef with him?

1465
01:42:30,979 --> 01:42:32,772
-One more thing.
-I can't wait.

1466
01:42:32,897 --> 01:42:37,652
It's simple. No one knows who fed you
this information. And I mean nobody.

1467
01:42:38,069 --> 01:42:39,279
How did you get it?

1468
01:42:39,404 --> 01:42:42,907
It fell into my lap.
Just like it's gonna fall into yours.

1469
01:42:49,164 --> 01:42:50,915
NICK: Christ Almighty.

1470
01:42:58,089 --> 01:43:02,093
-You got everything here but a confession.
-SHAKES: I thought I'd leave that up to you.

1471
01:43:02,177 --> 01:43:04,304
My preference is that you beat it out of him.

1472
01:43:04,429 --> 01:43:05,930
There's even surveillance photos.

1473
01:43:06,014 --> 01:43:09,767
This piece of shit's pulling in about
$5,000 a month, ripping off pushers.

1474
01:43:09,851 --> 01:43:12,103
-Has been for about three years.
-More like four.

1475
01:43:12,187 --> 01:43:14,814
-He ain't gonna see five.
-Got enough for a conviction?

1476
01:43:14,939 --> 01:43:17,817
That ain't up to me. That's up to a jury.

1477
01:43:20,612 --> 01:43:22,447
SHAKES: Show the jury this.

1478
01:43:24,699 --> 01:43:26,409
What do you got there, Ness?

1479
01:43:26,492 --> 01:43:28,912
About three weeks ago,
the body of a drug dealer

1480
01:43:28,995 --> 01:43:32,373
named Indian Red Lopez was found
in an alley in Jackson Heights.

1481
01:43:32,457 --> 01:43:34,834
Three bullets in his head,
nothing in his pockets.

1482
01:43:34,959 --> 01:43:36,127
I'm with you so far.

1483
01:43:36,211 --> 01:43:39,130
This is the gun that killed him,
and these are the shells.

1484
01:43:40,632 --> 01:43:42,675
What's behind door number three?

1485
01:43:42,800 --> 01:43:45,720
The prints on the gun belong to Adam Styler.

1486
01:43:49,140 --> 01:43:51,392
-(LAUGHS) Do me a favor, will you?
-What's that?

1487
01:43:51,476 --> 01:43:54,437
If I ever make it onto your shit list,
give me a call.

1488
01:43:54,520 --> 01:43:56,856
Give me a chance to apologize.

1489
01:43:57,065 --> 01:43:59,484
SHAKES: So you need anything else,
you talk to Frank.

1490
01:43:59,567 --> 01:44:02,946
-He knows how to get a hold of me.
-Take care of yourself, kid.

1491
01:44:03,029 --> 01:44:06,658
-Water gets choppy out your way.
-I'll do what I can.

1492
01:44:09,535 --> 01:44:13,665
-Did you ever think of becoming a cop?
-And leave the good guys?

1493
01:44:31,099 --> 01:44:33,268
-The body of Christ.
-Amen.

1494
01:44:42,360 --> 01:44:44,362
The body of Christ.

1495
01:44:52,578 --> 01:44:53,955
Amen.

1496
01:44:56,916 --> 01:44:58,418
The body of Christ.

1497
01:45:01,921 --> 01:45:04,132
SHAKES: Michael had done
all that could be expected

1498
01:45:04,215 --> 01:45:07,635
of an Assistant District Attorney
seeking a conviction.

1499
01:45:07,719 --> 01:45:12,265
He had a forensic expert detail the make
and caliber of the gun that killed Nokes.

1500
01:45:12,390 --> 01:45:15,226
He just never had the murder weapon
to present as evidence.

1501
01:45:15,310 --> 01:45:18,730
And he never gave the jury
a motive for the murder

1502
01:45:19,147 --> 01:45:21,774
The tension of his task,
the hours he was working,

1503
01:45:21,899 --> 01:45:24,902
and the uncertainty about the outcome
weighed heavily on him.

1504
01:45:24,986 --> 01:45:26,321
Did you see their faces?

1505
01:45:26,404 --> 01:45:29,157
Yes, I looked at them,
and they looked at me.

1506
01:45:29,240 --> 01:45:30,616
Did they say anything to you?

1507
01:45:30,742 --> 01:45:33,328
No, they just looked at me
and walked out of McHale's.

1508
01:45:33,411 --> 01:45:35,830
Are you sure the two defendants
killed Sean Nokes?

1509
01:45:35,913 --> 01:45:37,332
I know they killed him.

1510
01:45:37,415 --> 01:45:40,335
SHAKES: If the plan worked,
it would be everyone's success.

1511
01:45:40,418 --> 01:45:42,628
If it failed, the fault would fall to Michael.

1512
01:45:46,132 --> 01:45:50,053
Father Bobby Carillo, the priest with
the best hook shot on the West Side,

1513
01:45:50,136 --> 01:45:54,098
remained the key to a plan that called
for all involved to get away with murder

1514
01:45:54,223 --> 01:45:58,019
Did you turn around, look behind you,
when you heard the shooting, Mr. Carson?

1515
01:45:58,102 --> 01:46:00,146
Why didn't you turn around, Mr. Carson?

1516
01:46:00,271 --> 01:46:02,815
I was concerned for my companion's safety.

1517
01:46:02,940 --> 01:46:05,109
Did the two individuals
threaten you in any way?

1518
01:46:05,234 --> 01:46:06,277
No.

1519
01:46:06,402 --> 01:46:10,573
Did they threaten anyone
in McHale's Restaurant, as far as you know?

1520
01:46:10,656 --> 01:46:12,325
MR. CARSON: I didn't See it, but I know it.

1521
01:46:12,450 --> 01:46:15,286
SNYDER: If you didn't see the defendants
shoot the guy

1522
01:46:15,411 --> 01:46:18,623
then how do you know
it was the defendants that shot him?

1523
01:46:41,354 --> 01:46:43,314
What's the emergency?

1524
01:46:46,818 --> 01:46:49,404
Shakes shouldn't have sent you.
It's too risky.

1525
01:46:49,487 --> 01:46:52,490
Nobody sent me. I wanted to see you.

1526
01:46:54,659 --> 01:46:55,827
Why?

1527
01:46:57,036 --> 01:47:00,081
Shakes met with Father Bobby
two weeks ago.

1528
01:47:00,164 --> 01:47:04,836
-He hasn't heard from him since.
-It's not an overnight decision for him.

1529
01:47:07,213 --> 01:47:11,384
-What if he doesn't testify?
-Then we got a very serious problem.

1530
01:47:26,023 --> 01:47:28,860
Have Shakes talk to Father Bobby again.

1531
01:47:30,194 --> 01:47:34,115
Have him tell him the whole story.
He'll know what that means.

1532
01:47:34,198 --> 01:47:35,867
He already has.

1533
01:47:36,868 --> 01:47:38,077
What?

1534
01:47:40,580 --> 01:47:43,749
I was with him
when he talked to Father Bobby.

1535
01:47:45,918 --> 01:47:48,212
I heard everything, Michael.

1536
01:47:57,930 --> 01:47:59,557
So you know.

1537
01:48:01,893 --> 01:48:03,227
Yeah.

1538
01:48:07,190 --> 01:48:09,108
If only you'd told me...

1539
01:48:13,738 --> 01:48:16,574
I think things could've been different.

1540
01:48:18,075 --> 01:48:20,077
If you could've talked.

1541
01:48:24,582 --> 01:48:26,626
(CRYING) Maybe...

1542
01:48:53,778 --> 01:48:55,279
(JAZZ MUSIC PLAYING)

1543
01:48:55,363 --> 01:48:56,864
Hey, how you doing?

1544
01:48:56,948 --> 01:49:00,952
Carmine, that diet is working.
I don't care what anybody says.

1545
01:49:02,411 --> 01:49:06,374
-You still have a thing for Doris Day.
-She was a good woman.

1546
01:49:07,708 --> 01:49:09,627
You know the strega?

1547
01:49:10,086 --> 01:49:13,381
It's hard to miss a lady
with four warts and only one eye.

1548
01:49:13,464 --> 01:49:15,800
She needs the heads.

1549
01:49:21,305 --> 01:49:23,432
Take this to the witch.

1550
01:49:24,308 --> 01:49:26,227
Now, why does she need the heads?

1551
01:49:26,310 --> 01:49:29,146
-She takes the eyes.
-Wonderful.

1552
01:49:29,230 --> 01:49:32,984
Puts them in a bowl and mixes them
with water and oil.

1553
01:49:33,317 --> 01:49:34,819
And then?

1554
01:49:36,153 --> 01:49:38,948
People get headaches, they go to her.

1555
01:49:39,115 --> 01:49:42,076
She looks into their eyes and tells them

1556
01:49:42,159 --> 01:49:44,245
who is wishing the headaches.

1557
01:49:44,328 --> 01:49:48,165
She says a few words
and the headaches go away.

1558
01:49:48,624 --> 01:49:52,962
Once in a while the person who wishes
the headaches goes away, too.

1559
01:49:53,963 --> 01:49:57,508
This guy, Addison,
the one who works for the Mayor,

1560
01:49:57,800 --> 01:50:00,177
he quits his job in two weeks.

1561
01:50:00,761 --> 01:50:04,348
He don't want nobody to know
what kind of a guy he is.

1562
01:50:04,432 --> 01:50:08,519
He don't want nobody to see
pictures of him they shouldn't see.

1563
01:50:09,020 --> 01:50:11,147
-He knows this?
-He will.

1564
01:50:12,440 --> 01:50:14,775
The boys he buys for parties are expensive.

1565
01:50:14,859 --> 01:50:18,821
Now, Addison makes good money,
but he don't make real money.

1566
01:50:19,780 --> 01:50:21,198
How much does he owe?

1567
01:50:21,282 --> 01:50:24,785
$8,000 with a heavy vig. I paid that off.

1568
01:50:25,494 --> 01:50:26,871
You paid?

1569
01:50:27,496 --> 01:50:30,041
Addison's debts belong to me now.

1570
01:50:31,125 --> 01:50:33,794
-You hate debts.
-I hate Addison.

1571
01:50:36,380 --> 01:50:40,134
We're in the dirty end of the field now.
That's where I play.

1572
01:50:40,217 --> 01:50:42,303
And I like to play alone.

1573
01:50:42,386 --> 01:50:46,682
You're a nice kid. You always were.
Don't let this change it.

1574
01:51:00,363 --> 01:51:03,157
SHAKES: His mother named him
Edward Goldenberg Robinson

1575
01:51:03,240 --> 01:51:05,409
after her favorite actor

1576
01:51:05,534 --> 01:51:07,328
To continue the Hollywood connection

1577
01:51:07,411 --> 01:51:10,164
Eddie Robinson took the street name
Little Caesar

1578
01:51:10,247 --> 01:51:13,751
as he made his way up the ranks
of the lucrative drug trade.

1579
01:51:13,834 --> 01:51:17,505
He had a 12-year-old son
in a private school in upstate New York.

1580
01:51:17,588 --> 01:51:20,174
He named him Rizzo,
after his youngest brother;

1581
01:51:20,257 --> 01:51:24,011
who died while in the custody
of the Wilkinson Home for Boys.

1582
01:51:24,095 --> 01:51:27,264
-I want you to give me some money.
-All right.

1583
01:51:27,807 --> 01:51:29,517
I'll play along.

1584
01:51:29,809 --> 01:51:33,646
-How long before you pay it back?
-I ain't paying it back.

1585
01:51:33,729 --> 01:51:35,523
Somebody else is.

1586
01:51:37,608 --> 01:51:39,193
This somebody I know?

1587
01:51:39,276 --> 01:51:42,613
-Your little brother knew him.
-Rizzo?

1588
01:51:45,366 --> 01:51:47,034
How did he know Rizzo?

1589
01:51:47,118 --> 01:51:51,414
Henry Addison was a guard
in an upstate reform school.

1590
01:51:52,081 --> 01:51:56,127
He was there the same time as Rizzo,
before and after he died.

1591
01:52:02,007 --> 01:52:04,927
Count out $8,000, put it in an envelope.

1592
01:52:10,725 --> 01:52:13,102
You go back a long time, old man.

1593
01:52:14,145 --> 01:52:15,980
Old men always do.

1594
01:52:16,105 --> 01:52:19,024
Ran with the guineas
back when the guineas were tough.

1595
01:52:19,108 --> 01:52:20,943
I ran when I could.

1596
01:52:21,610 --> 01:52:23,779
Looked good doing it, too.

1597
01:52:23,863 --> 01:52:25,990
(CHUCKLING)

1598
01:52:26,073 --> 01:52:29,869
Gave the business some style, some class.

1599
01:52:31,078 --> 01:52:35,541
Made it a call for respect
the way you wore it, the way you talked it.

1600
01:52:36,292 --> 01:52:38,711
I always liked that about you.

1601
01:52:38,794 --> 01:52:42,047
I'm no help to you. My tailor is dead.

1602
01:52:49,221 --> 01:52:53,309
I'll look up our friend
and collect the money he owes me.

1603
01:52:53,726 --> 01:52:58,606
-He owes you something more than money.
-Ain't nothing worth more than the green.

1604
01:52:58,939 --> 01:53:01,484
-This is.
-What, old man?

1605
01:53:02,359 --> 01:53:05,279
What's this guy owe
that means more than dollars?

1606
01:53:05,362 --> 01:53:09,325
He owes you Rizzo.
He's the man that killed your brother.

1607
01:53:18,751 --> 01:53:21,962
-They said he died of pneumonia.
-They said.

1608
01:53:29,553 --> 01:53:31,555
WEISMAN: What is the relevance of this?

1609
01:53:31,639 --> 01:53:34,433
So Ralph Ferguson
is a Sunday school teacher

1610
01:53:34,517 --> 01:53:38,103
I don't know, Counsel.
What you're asking is highly unusual.

1611
01:53:38,187 --> 01:53:42,942
I understand that, Your Honor.
Again, I need to put a face to the victim.

1612
01:53:43,609 --> 01:53:47,154
Otherwise, it's just another name
in the obituaries.

1613
01:53:47,613 --> 01:53:49,824
Mr. Snyder, any objections?

1614
01:53:51,242 --> 01:53:53,035
I don't have a problem with it.

1615
01:53:53,744 --> 01:53:58,541
Your Honor, the prosecution would like
to call Ralph Ferguson to the stand.

1616
01:54:23,941 --> 01:54:26,402
-Good morning, Mr. Ferguson.
-Good morning.

1617
01:54:26,485 --> 01:54:30,281
I thank you for coming.
I realize, for you, this has been a long trip.

1618
01:54:30,364 --> 01:54:33,617
I'm just sorry it had to be
for something like this.

1619
01:54:33,701 --> 01:54:36,203
You and the victim, Sean Nokes,
were good friends.

1620
01:54:36,287 --> 01:54:39,331
Your testimony as a character witness
will be very valuable.

1621
01:54:39,415 --> 01:54:42,835
We were great friends.
It would be hard to find a better friend.

1622
01:54:42,918 --> 01:54:47,464
-Would you say you were his best friend?
-I was his closest, that's for sure.

1623
01:54:47,548 --> 01:54:51,594
-How long did you know each other?
-About 17, 18 years.

1624
01:54:52,136 --> 01:54:55,514
-Did you see each other often?
-As often as we could.

1625
01:54:55,598 --> 01:54:59,393
Weekends, holidays, vacations,
things like that.

1626
01:55:00,519 --> 01:55:04,106
-What kind of man was Sean Nokes?
-He was a good man.

1627
01:55:04,189 --> 01:55:07,234
He was too good to be shot dead
by a couple of street punks.

1628
01:55:07,318 --> 01:55:09,695
Objection.
Statement is one of opinion, not fact.

1629
01:55:09,778 --> 01:55:13,407
-He was asked his opinion.
-Overruled. Please proceed.

1630
01:55:15,284 --> 01:55:19,455
Mr. Ferguson, were you aware
of any enemies he might have had?

1631
01:55:19,914 --> 01:55:22,082
Sean Nokes had no enemies.

1632
01:55:22,333 --> 01:55:25,878
Thank you, Mr. Ferguson.
I have no further questions.

1633
01:55:30,132 --> 01:55:31,926
SNYDER: What is that, a prison?

1634
01:55:32,009 --> 01:55:34,428
FERGUSON: No,
it's a juvenile facility for young boys.

1635
01:55:34,511 --> 01:55:37,640
Your function was what
at this juvenile facility?

1636
01:55:37,723 --> 01:55:39,308
Standard stuff.

1637
01:55:39,600 --> 01:55:43,646
Keep the boys in line,
make sure they got to class on time,

1638
01:55:44,104 --> 01:55:47,858
keep an eye out for trouble, put them down
for the night. Nothing exciting.

1639
01:55:47,942 --> 01:55:50,736
As guards, were you and Mr. Nokes allowed

1640
01:55:50,819 --> 01:55:54,657
to use force to, as you put it,
"keep the boys in line"?

1641
01:55:54,740 --> 01:55:58,577
-What do you mean, "force"?
-Were you allowed to hit them?

1642
01:55:58,702 --> 01:56:00,537
No, of course not.

1643
01:56:00,704 --> 01:56:02,998
Were any of the boys hit
by any of the guards

